Setting Up Environment

HittersAE2<-Hitters%>%subset(League=="A")%>%subset(Division=="E")
HittersNE2<-Hitters%>%subset(League=="N")%>%subset(Division=="E")
HittersNW2<-Hitters%>%subset(League=="N")%>%subset(Division=="W")
HittersAW2<-Hitters%>%subset(League=="A")%>%subset(Division=="W")

HittersAEclean<-HittersAE2%>% subset(!is.na(Salary))
HittersAWclean<-HittersAW2%>% subset(!is.na(Salary))
HittersNEclean<-HittersNE2%>% subset(!is.na(Salary))
HittersNWclean<-HittersNW2%>% subset(!is.na(Salary))

HittersAEclean.lars<-lars(as.matrix(HittersAEclean[,-c(20,19,14,15)]),HittersAEclean$Salary)
HittersAWclean.lars<-lars(as.matrix(HittersAWclean[,-c(20,19,14,15)]),HittersAWclean$Salary)
HittersNEclean.lars<-lars(as.matrix(HittersNEclean[,-c(20,19,14,15)]),HittersNEclean$Salary)
HittersNWclean.lars<-lars(as.matrix(HittersNWclean[,-c(20,19,14,15)]),HittersNWclean$Salary)

I1

I1<-HittersAEclean.lars$Cp==min(HittersAEclean.lars$Cp)

Discussion Questions

Is there a difference in distributions of salaries between the 4 divisions?

  • Yes there is a difference in distributions of the salaries between 4 divisions, there is no single multicollinearity between all divisions.

Is there a difference in the way salary depends on performance between the 4 divisions? 1 look at all 4 divisions

  • There is an observed difference in the way salary depends on performance between the 4 divisions. In general, heteroscedascity is observed among all plots.

2 For each division choose the minimal Cp lars model (20 points each division, 80 points total)

  • The division with the minimal CP lars model is AE.

Check with scatterplots the predictions using the minimal CP lars model from the chosen division against actual salaries for each division (4 scatterplots, construct 4 predictions based on the 1 model ). After you do this for all 4 divisions (16 scatterplots) Use this to decide if it looks like there is a uniform process based on performance for choosing salary or not. Argue why or why not.

  • I do not think there is a uniform process. If there was a uniform process based on performance than there should be no variation between players having a linear relationship between all divisions, rather there are extreme outliers indicating that there is no uniformity between the grpahs.

3 After youve done steo 2 building the lars model 4 times (so 16 plots) compare the lars and lm model for the same variables predicting the salary for 1 division (1 scatterplot) (20 points)

  • The relationship between the predicted AE and lmAE graphs shows an almost perfect linear relationship.

Compare the prediction (eg. just AElars vs AElm) and the coefficients. What have the coefficients done between Lars and LM???

  • Between the two graphs, holding all other variables constant, both AElars and AElm have similar coefficients, i.e. Hits (10.0477, 10.47129) respectively. This means that both have similar coefficients so that at each unit increase allows for each coefficient to affect each players wage similarly thus allowing for an almost perfect linear relationship between the two graphs.
